com.constantcontact.util.http
Class HttpsAuthProcessor

java.lang.Object
  com.constantcontact.util.http.HttpsAuthProcessor
All Implemented Interfaces:
ProcessorBase
public class HttpsAuthProcessor
extends Object
implements ProcessorBase

Implementation for OAuth2 authentication schema.
Handle HTTPS and HTTP authentication handshake in Constant Contact.
Manage the cookies flow using an internal instance of CookieManager.
Manage the calls flow using an AuthenticationConnection.
It is not a good practice to call methods from this class directly. You should consider calling the CtcOAuth2 methods.

Author:
ConstantContact

Method Detail

makeAuthRequest

public AuthResponse makeAuthRequest(String callUrl,
                                    String keyFromHeader,
                                    ProcessorBase.HttpMethod httpMethod,
                                    String data)
                             throws ConstantContactAuthenticationException
Used by all authentication calls to send data to server side and get the response.
It automatically adds the cookies in the cookie store using the internal cookieManager.

Parameters:
callUrl - The Url to call
keyFromHeader - The key from header for which we need data to be returned.
Usually we are interested in the Location.
httpMethod - The HTTP Method
data - The data to send to the server, if any.
GET calls will not send any data.
Returns:
An AuthResponse, containing the entry from HTTP response header specified by key.
The AuthResponse.getRedirectUrl() can be used to retrieve the redirect location as provided by the server (if any location was provided).
Throws:
ConstantContactAuthenticationException - When there is a problem in the authentication flow / server answered with an unexpected response.

requestLoginPage

public void requestLoginPage(String loginUrl)
                      throws ConstantContactAuthenticationException
First phase in the authentication flow: request the login page (the one containing the login form).
We're not interested in the form at all, since we don't process any data inside it. BUT we are VERY interested in the cookies!
The first call will bounce recursively a couple of times, until server answers with 200 HTTP code.
This is the only way to do it, since a single call won't set all the needed cookies and the rest of the flow would be crippled.

Parameters:
loginUrl - The URL where to make the GET call
Throws:
ConstantContactAuthenticationException - When there is a problem in the authentication flow / server answered with an unexpected response.

submitAuthenticationRequest

public String submitAuthenticationRequest()
                                   throws ConstantContactAuthenticationException
Second phase in the authentication handshake.
This will mimic the request in which we submit the authentication request : submit of the authentication form.
In real browser scenario, after the form is submitted, server should redirect a user to the grand access page.
We are actually just capturing the URL of that page, and return it for usage in the next steps.

Returns:
Upon success, this will provide us with the grand Access Url. An exception is thrown otherwise.
Throws:
ConstantContactAuthenticationException - When there is a problem in the authentication flow / server answered with an unexpected response.

requestGrandAccess

public void requestGrandAccess(String grandAccessUrl)
                        throws ConstantContactAuthenticationException
Third phase in the authentication flow: mimics the click on the Grant Access button by making a POST call.
Since the POST call comes back with a redirect, we must also make a GET call to the location provided by the server (because that's what a browser does and we need to mimic that behavior).
The GET call is made in requestGrandAccessStage2(String)

Parameters:
grandAccessUrl - The Grand Access Url, as returned by submitAuthenticationRequest()
Throws:
ConstantContactAuthenticationException - When there is a problem in the authentication flow / server answered with an unexpected response.

requestGrandAccessStage2

public void requestGrandAccessStage2(String accessUrl)
                              throws ConstantContactAuthenticationException
Second step of the third phase : the GET call made for the Grand Access.
This should bounce recursively until HTTP 200 is returned by the server side.

Parameters:
accessUrl - The access url, as the server returned inside requestGrandAccess(String)
Throws:
ConstantContactAuthenticationException - When there is a problem in the authentication flow / server answered with an unexpected response.

requestAuthorization

public String requestAuthorization()
                            throws ConstantContactAuthenticationException
Forth and last step of the authentication flow.
Mimics the click on the Grant Access button in a browser - which actually submits a form to the server side.
We're are just making a POST call to the specific URL, appending all the needed form data and cookies.

Returns:
Returns a string containing an URL like http://www.constantcontact.com/index.jsp#access_token=YOUR_TOKEN&token_type=Bearer&expires_in=313274874
Throws:
ConstantContactAuthenticationException - When there is a problem in the authentication flow / server answered with an unexpected response.

addCookieHeaders

public void addCookieHeaders()
Add cookie headers to the current instance of AuthenticationConnection depending on the domain name.
Cookies are extracted from the Cookie Store found in the local Cookie Manager.
Cookies will be stored in a single header entry, and separated by ; just as HTTP protocol requires.
Handles both :
  • perfect domain match (such as oauth2.constantcontact.com);
  • partial domain match (such as .constantcontact.com);
